# ------- FHIR-31720: Add new R5 Subscription resources -------

+5s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Okay, first item. FHIR-31720 — Add new R5 Subscription resources. This is about making sure the R6 ballot includes the SubscriptionTopic and SubscriptionStatus resources that were introduced in R5. The ballot comment says these resources are listed as trial-use in R5 but should be normative for R6."
+3s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="My proposed disposition is persuasive with modification. We agree that SubscriptionTopic and SubscriptionStatus should be targeted for normative in R6, but with the caveat that the canFilterBy changes from FHIR-32752 need to be incorporated first. We can't make something normative that has a known structural issue."
+3s say speaker="Grahame Grieve" text="I agree with the disposition. These resources have been through enough implementation cycles via the backport IG that they should qualify for normative. The FMM evidence is there."

+2s say speaker="Brian Postlethwaite" text="How many implementations do we have? I want to make sure we're not just counting the backport IG adopters as R5 implementations."
+3s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Good question. For SubscriptionTopic specifically, we have: Microsoft's reference implementation, HAPI FHIR, Smile CDR, two Epic endpoints that are in production, the Aidbox implementation, and the Firely Vonk implementation. That's seven independent implementations. The backport IG implementations are separate — those are R4 implementations using the cross-version extension approach."
+2s say speaker="James Agnew" text="I can confirm HAPI FHIR has had SubscriptionTopic support since version 6.4. It's been stable. We do see some rough edges with canFilterBy, which is why I voted for FHIR-32752 as well."
+2s say speaker="Brian Postlethwaite" text="Okay, seven is solid. I'm comfortable."

+3s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Any other discussion? Hearing none. Motion to accept FHIR-31720 as persuasive with modification per Gino's proposal. Gino moves, who seconds?"
+1s say speaker="James Agnew" text="Second."
+2s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Gino Canessa/James Agnew. All in favor? Opposed? Abstentions?"
+2s say speaker="Rick Geimer" text="Persuasive with Mod: Gino Canessa/James Agnew: 16-0-0."

# ------- FHIR-31063: Subscriptions over SMART Web Messaging -------

+5s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Next up — FHIR-31063. Support FHIR Subscriptions over SMART Web Messaging. This one's been sitting in the tracker for a while. The submitter wants subscription notifications to be deliverable via SMART Web Messaging channels, not just REST hooks, websockets, and email."
+3s say speaker="Josh Mandel" text="I should probably recuse myself from voting since I'm one of the SMART Web Messaging editors, but I can provide context. The idea is that if you have an EHR that's already running a SMART app in an iframe, you should be able to push subscription notifications into that app via the existing postMessage channel rather than requiring the app to maintain a separate REST endpoint or websocket connection."
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Right. And my proposed disposition is persuasive with modification. We'd add SMART Web Messaging as a channel type in R6, but mark it as trial-use since the SMART Web Messaging spec itself is still maturing."

+4s say speaker="John Moehrke" text="I have a security concern here. SMART Web Messaging uses postMessage, which has a well-known history of cross-origin vulnerabilities. If we're pushing clinical data through that channel, we need to make sure the security considerations are thorough."
+3s say speaker="Josh Mandel" text="That's fair, John. The SMART Web Messaging spec does address origin verification, but I agree the subscription-specific security considerations should be explicit. Things like: the EHR must verify the SMART app's origin before delivering notifications, notifications should not include full resource content by default — use the id-only notification type so the app has to fetch via the existing authorized FHIR connection."
+3s say speaker="John Moehrke" text="Id-only by default is a good mitigation. I'd want that to be a SHALL, not a SHOULD."
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="I'm okay with that as a modification. SMART Web Messaging channel type SHALL default to id-only notification content."

+3s say speaker="Vassil Peytchev" text="From a practical standpoint, does anyone actually need this? Our SMART apps currently use websockets for real-time updates and it works fine."
+2s say speaker="Josh Mandel" text="It matters most for contexts where websockets aren't available — like embedded browser views in mobile EHR apps, or environments with aggressive proxy servers that strip websocket upgrades. SMART Web Messaging works in those contexts because it's just postMessage."
+2s say speaker="Vassil Peytchev" text="Fair enough. I won't block it."

+2s chat id=chat-3 from="Jose Costa Teixeira" to="Everyone" text="This could be useful for the WHO SMART Guidelines work where connectivity constraints make websockets unreliable."
+2s chat id=chat-4 from="John Moehrke" to="Everyone" text="Security review checklist for subscription channels: https://build.fhir.org/safety.html — sections 6 and 7 are relevant"

+3s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Okay, I think we have a path. Motion to accept FHIR-31063 as persuasive with modification: add SMART Web Messaging channel type as trial-use, with SHALL default to id-only notification content. Motion?"
+1s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="So moved."
+1s say speaker="John Moehrke" text="Second."
+2s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Gino Canessa/John Moehrke. All in favor? Opposed? Abstentions?"
+2s say speaker="Josh Mandel" text="Abstaining due to conflict of interest."
+1s say speaker="Rick Geimer" text="Persuasive with Mod: Gino Canessa/John Moehrke: 15-0-1. Josh Mandel abstaining."

# ------- FHIR-31470: Missing notification type details -------

+5s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="FHIR-31470 — Missing notification type details. This is about the fact that the subscription notification bundle doesn't clearly document the differences between full-resource, id-only, and empty notification content levels. The ballot comment says the descriptions are 'woefully inadequate' — their words, not mine."
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="I think this is straightforwardly persuasive. We just need better documentation. I've drafted expanded descriptions with examples for each content level."
+2s say speaker="Grahame Grieve" text="I've reviewed Gino's draft. It's good. The examples are clear. I'd suggest we also add a table comparing the three levels side by side."
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Good idea. I'll add that."

+2s say speaker="Eric Haas" text="Can we also clarify what happens when a server doesn't support the requested content level? Right now it's ambiguous. If I request full-resource but the server only supports id-only, does it error or downgrade silently?"
+3s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Currently the spec says the server MAY return a lower content level. But I agree that's confusing. Proposal: server SHOULD return the requested level or reject the subscription with an OperationOutcome explaining what's supported."
+2s say speaker="Eric Haas" text="SHOULD, not SHALL?"
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="SHOULD. There are edge cases where a server might not be able to deliver full-resource for security reasons — like if the resource was deleted and the content is no longer available. In those cases, downgrading to id-only is correct behavior."
+2s say speaker="Eric Haas" text="Okay, SHOULD works. I can live with that."

+2s chat id=chat-5 from="Richard Ettema" to="Everyone" text="AEGIS has test scripts for all three notification levels in Touchstone. Happy to share the test results as FMM evidence."
+2s chat id=chat-6 from="Brian Postlethwaite" to="Everyone" text="Do we need a fourth level? 'empty-with-count' has come up in a few implementations where the client just wants to know HOW MANY things changed."
+3s chat id=chat-7 from="Gino Canessa" to="Everyone" text="@Brian let's track that as a separate R7 proposal. R6 scope is already tight enough." reply_to=chat-6

+3s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Let's vote. Motion to accept FHIR-31470 as persuasive with modification per Gino's expanded documentation plus the SHOULD language on content level negotiation. Motion?"
+1s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="So moved."
+1s say speaker="Eric Haas" text="Second."
+2s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Gino Canessa/Eric Haas. All in favor? Opposed? Abstentions? Unanimous."
+1s say speaker="Rick Geimer" text="Persuasive with Mod: Gino Canessa/Eric Haas: 16-0-0."

# ------- Heated exchange about SubscriptionTopic discovery -------

+5s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Okay, next cluster of items. FHIR-32772 — Clarify authorization rules for the SubscriptionTopic status endpoint. And it connects to a broader question about topic discovery that several commenters raised."
+3s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="The issue is: how does a client discover what SubscriptionTopics a server supports? Right now, you do a search on SubscriptionTopic, but servers may not want to expose all topics to all clients. A client with a patient-level scope shouldn't necessarily see system-level administrative topics."
+4s say speaker="Josh Mandel" text="This is the SMART scoping question. Currently there's no defined scope for SubscriptionTopic. You'd need something like system/SubscriptionTopic.read, but that's a very broad grant. Ideally you'd want topic-specific scopes, but that gets complicated fast."
+3s say speaker="Vassil Peytchev" text="We've been struggling with this internally. Our current approach is to filter the SubscriptionTopic search results based on the client's existing resource scopes. If a client has patient/Observation.read, they can see topics related to Observation. But that's a heuristic, not a standard."
+2s say speaker="Cooper Thompson" text="Same approach at our end. But it's fragile. What if a topic spans multiple resource types? Like an admission topic that involves Encounter, Patient, and Location?"

+4s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="This is exactly the problem the ballot comments are raising. My proposed disposition for FHIR-32772 is persuasive with modification. We add guidance that servers SHOULD filter SubscriptionTopic search results based on the client's authorization context, but we don't prescribe the exact filtering algorithm because it depends on the authorization model."
+3s say speaker="John Moehrke" text="That's too vague. 'SHOULD filter based on authorization context' could mean anything. We need at least a normative statement about what MUST NOT happen — for example, a server MUST NOT return SubscriptionTopics that reference resource types the client is not authorized to access."
+3s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Okay, I can strengthen it to include a MUST NOT. That gives implementers a clear floor without over-constraining the algorithm."

+2s say speaker="Grahame Grieve" text="I want to push back slightly. Do we actually have the evidence that this is a real security problem? Has anyone demonstrated an information leakage attack via SubscriptionTopic discovery?"
+3s say speaker="John Moehrke" text="Grahame, you don't need a demonstrated attack to have a security requirement. The principle of least privilege means you shouldn't expose metadata about resources the client can't access. Full stop. We've been over this with every resource that has a search endpoint."
+2s say speaker="Grahame Grieve" text="I agree with the principle. I'm just questioning whether the MUST NOT is testable. How does a test verify that a server didn't return a topic it shouldn't have, without knowing the server's full topic set?"
+3s say speaker="John Moehrke" text="The same way you test any negative requirement — you set up a test context with known topics and scopes, and verify the response matches expectations. Richard's Touchstone tests can do this."
+2s say speaker="Richard Ettema" text="Confirmed, we can write that test. It's not trivial but it's doable."

+2s chat id=chat-8 from="Alexander Henket" to="Everyone" text="NICTIZ has similar requirements for the Dutch infrastructure. We filter topics by organization-level authorization grants."
+2s chat id=chat-9 from="James Agnew" to="Everyone" text="HAPI FHIR currently doesn't filter SubscriptionTopic search results at all. We'd need to add this. It's not a small change."

+4s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="James, I appreciate the honesty. Would the MUST NOT be a problem for HAPI?"
+3s say speaker="James Agnew" text="It means we'd need to integrate the authorization layer with the topic search, which we currently don't. It's maybe a two-sprint effort. Not catastrophic, but I want to flag it as real implementation work."
+2s say speaker="Eric Haas" text="Two sprints to not leak information seems like a reasonable investment."
+2s say speaker="James Agnew" text="Oh, I agree. I'm not arguing against it. Just sizing the impact for the group."

+3s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Okay, I think we have consensus on the direction. Motion to accept FHIR-32772 as persuasive with modification: add MUST NOT return SubscriptionTopics referencing resource types outside the client's authorized scope, plus SHOULD guidance on filtering based on broader authorization context. Motion?"
+1s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="So moved."
+1s say speaker="John Moehrke" text="Second."
+2s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Gino Canessa/John Moehrke. All in favor? Opposed? Abstentions?"
+2s say speaker="Rick Geimer" text="Persuasive with Mod: Gino Canessa/John Moehrke: 16-0-0."

# ------- Lighter moment: the backport IG joke -------

+5s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Okay, before the next batch, I want to address the elephant in the room. Several ballot comments reference the backport IG and ask whether it's still needed post-R6. The answer is: yes, because R4 isn't going away anytime soon, and the backport IG bridges R4 to R5-era subscriptions."
+3s say speaker="Eric Haas" text="Gino, you've been maintaining the backport IG for, what, four years now? At some point we should give you a FHIR hat that says 'I survived the subscription rewrite.'"
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="I already have three FHIR hats. What I need is for people to stop asking me to backport R6 features to R4. There's a limit to how many versions I can hold in my head simultaneously."
+3s say speaker="Grahame Grieve" text="There's no limit, Gino. You're the subscription guru. Gurus don't get limits."
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Gurus get burnout, Grahame."
+2s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Noted. Let's add 'prevent Gino burnout' to the R7 roadmap."

+2s chat id=chat-10 from="Ward Weistra" to="Everyone" text="Subscription guru support group meets Wednesdays on chat.fhir.org #subscriptions"
+2s chat id=chat-11 from="Ewout Kramer" to="Everyone" text="We should start a FHIReside Chat podcast episode about subscription trauma" reply_to=chat-10

