# ------- WebSocket vs. REST hook performance debate -------

+5s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Last substantial item for today — a cluster of comments about WebSocket versus REST hook performance. Several commenters are asking for guidance on when to use which channel type. The spec currently says 'implementations may choose' but doesn't help with the choice."
+4s say speaker="Brian Postlethwaite" text="This is a real pain point for us. We support both, and our users constantly ask which one they should use. REST hooks are simpler to set up but have higher latency due to the HTTP round-trip per notification. WebSockets are lower latency but harder to scale behind a load balancer."
+3s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Right. My proposal is to add an informative section — not normative — with guidance on channel type selection. REST hooks for: low-volume, server-to-server, behind firewalls. WebSockets for: high-volume, real-time UI updates, single-client scenarios. Email for: low-priority, human-readable alerts. And SMART Web Messaging for: embedded app contexts."
+3s say speaker="James Agnew" text="I'd add one thing: REST hooks with bundled notifications. A lot of implementations miss that you can batch multiple notifications into a single bundle delivery. That dramatically reduces the HTTP overhead for high-volume REST hook scenarios."
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Good point. I'll include bundling guidance under the REST hook section."

+3s say speaker="Ewout Kramer" text="Can we also address the heartbeat question? WebSocket connections that go silent for too long get killed by intermediate proxies. The current spec says servers SHOULD send heartbeat notifications but doesn't specify an interval."
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="I've been advocating for a default heartbeat of sixty seconds for WebSocket channels. That's aggressive enough to keep proxies happy without generating excessive traffic."
+2s say speaker="Brian Postlethwaite" text="Sixty seconds is fine. Some of our environments have thirty-second proxy timeouts, but the server can negotiate that down at subscription creation time."
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Right, the heartbeat period should be configurable per-subscription. The sixty seconds is just the default when the client doesn't specify."

+2s chat id=chat-12 from="Craig Newman" to="Everyone" text="For reference: AWS API Gateway has a 10-minute idle timeout for WebSocket connections. Azure has 4 minutes. GCP has 60 seconds."
+2s chat id=chat-13 from="Vassil Peytchev" to="Everyone" text="Our load balancers use 30s timeouts. 60s default heartbeat would not work for us." reply_to=chat-12
+2s chat id=chat-14 from="Gino Canessa" to="Everyone" text="@Vassil that's why the heartbeat is configurable — you'd set it to 25s for your environment" reply_to=chat-13

+3s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="This sounds like informative guidance, not a normative change. Can we vote on adding the section?"
+2s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Motion to add informative channel type selection guidance section to the Subscriptions page, including heartbeat recommendations. Motion?"
+1s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="So moved."
+1s say speaker="Brian Postlethwaite" text="Second."
+2s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Gino Canessa/Brian Postlethwaite. All in favor? Opposed? Abstentions? Unanimous."
+1s say speaker="Rick Geimer" text="Persuasive with Mod: Gino Canessa/Brian Postlethwaite: 16-0-0."

# ------- Wrap up -------

+5s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="All right, excellent progress. We got through twelve items today with nine to go. I'd like to schedule a follow-up call for next Monday to finish the remaining items. Gino, does that work?"
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="Works for me. The remaining items are mostly about error handling and retry semantics. Should be less contentious."
+2s say speaker="Eric Haas" text="Famous last words from the subscription guru."
+2s say speaker="Gino Canessa" text="I walked into that one."

+3s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="One more housekeeping item — the R6 content freeze is November first. That's eleven days away. If anyone has outstanding tracker items that affect subscriptions, please file them NOW. Not next week. Now."
+2s say speaker="Grahame Grieve" text="And make sure to use the FHIR project in JIRA, not the old gForge tracker. I still get items submitted to gForge and it's 2025."
+2s say speaker="Eric Haas" text="Some habits die hard. Like using Conformance instead of CapabilityStatement."
+2s say speaker="Grahame Grieve" text="Eric, if you call it Conformance one more time, I'm going to rename it to CapabilityFeatureDeclarationStatement just to spite everyone."
+2s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Please don't."

+3s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Thank you all for your time. We made good progress today. Twelve items resolved, nine remaining. Next call is Monday the twenty-seventh, same time. Rick, please post the minutes to Confluence."
+2s say speaker="Rick Geimer" text="Will do. Minutes will be up by end of day."
+2s say speaker="Lloyd McKenzie" text="Meeting adjourned. Have a good week everyone."

